segments.text: I have an indication here that you served for a couple years as an officer in the architectural club.
Yes.
Was that only architectural majors, or could other students belong to that, too?
There weren't majors there.
They're just architects.
Yeah, that's right.
And you were at what?
Were you in the college of agriculture?
I was president of it the last year, yes.
Was that, let's see, was that point it was in the College of Agriculture, wasn't it?
More or less landscape architecture?
Engineering.
Engineering.
Dean Nigel's school.
Who was your faculty sponsor, if you recall?
I'm assuming that the club has had faculty sponsors then as they do now.
Well, we had two.
Our first was Alice Berger.
And then the last year was, I don't recall his name now, but he was head of the department.
Was this architectural club tied in with some other, a nationwide students professional organization or it was just a local thing?
Was it primarily, was it more inclined towards a professional aspect of architecture or was it really more of a social organization?
Professional.
Professional.
You met, regulated to discuss architectural problems then?
Yes.
And I also had an indication, you were an assistant editor of the Architectural Yearbook.
Was that a fairly common thing then?
Did the various disciplines publish separate yearbooks?
Well, the architectural department had a yearbook, yes.
This would be what?
Did you have pictures of the students in them?
Mostly student work.
It would be drawings that the students had done during the year.
There were projects they had done during the year.
And then as the editor and assistant editor, I guess, would be the ones who would choose which drawings would appear in the book?
With the faculty.
They always worked with us.
And you also were on the battalion staff for a couple of years, I believe.
Yes.
What role did you play on that?
Old little cartoons once in a while.
Anything else?
No, I don't.
As art editor of the Longhorn, I gather you did most of the drawings that appear.
No, a big part of that job is getting the other guys to work for you.
I did quite a few and I really enjoyed it.
In previous years you did some of the drawings for other editors.
Yes.
Did the art editor have anything to do with the makeup of the Longhorn or did the printer decide in what order the various segments?
Now I know the Longhorn is divided into the various classes and has the military aspects and the social clubs and so forth.
Did you have much to say about how it was organized, or did somebody else do that?
No, no.
I don't know whether student staff did that, but they, in general, followed the pattern of previous issues.
Okay, and I believe you were also a member of the Ross Volunteers.
Yes.
Was that for one year or two?
Just one, last year.
And how were you named to that organization?
I think my roommate got me in.
It wasn't my military ability.
Okay, it was supposed to have been, even at that point I believe, it was supposed to have been somewhat of a crack drill team.
Did you do a lot of extra drilling?
Yes, we did.
Okay, and so you had...
Double drill then, I take it, with your regular company?
Well, not really double, but extra.
Uh-huh.
Regular drill with your company?
Yes.
And about how often did you have that, if you recall?
The RV drills?
No, the regular company drill.
Oh, I think every day.
Uh-huh.
For about how long?
Oh, in the afternoon, for an hour or so.
And then how much did you drill for the RVs?
I don't know, probably once a week or something like that.
What did the Ross Volunteers as a group, what did they do or what was their contribution to the school, I should say?
Did they serve any function other than... Well, they served as an honor guard on special occasions and
I think that was the principal thing.
And I think they had a dance, a big dance.
Oh, yes, the RV dance in the spring was one of the three big dances.
What were the other two?
The Thanksgiving hop and the final ball.
And I believe you had something to do with the decoration of one of the Thanksgiving tops.
Oh, yeah, I got rubbed on that, too.
Would this be something that would take you an awful lot of time to prepare all the decorations, or...?
Not a great deal.
These were held where?
In Spiesel Hall.
Spiesel Hall.
So you would have to, what, kind of get the people together to clear out after you'd had the regular meal or it was in the same dining area where you had the regular meal?
Yes, they gave us a paper sack lunch at noon and then we cleared the hall.
So you had the whole afternoon then to get it ready?
Yes.
I think about the, I had more fun than I would have at one of the dances, but
They put meal on the floor, and then we'd take bales of hay with ropes tied around them, and after we swept the meal off, polished this floor.
And some of the girls came down there peeping in, and we got them in there and were having chariot races with them on those bales of hay.
This would be some of the girls that had come down for dancing?
For the dance.
So this was when you were cleaning up after the dance?
No, this was before the dance, polishing the floor.
Oh, to get the floor polished.
So you said they put meal on the floor?
They put meal on it for several days so you wouldn't spill anything on it.
And then when they swept that off, you had to polish the floor.
This was so it would be nice and smooth for the dance?
That's right.
I imagine those chariot races must have been something to behold.
A lot of fun.
We slept that in on the upperclassmen.
You graduated then in the spring of 1920.
And I presume you either had or sought a job at that point.
Did you have a job?
Yes, I had a job when I graduated and I went to Abilene and I was out there about seven years in the same office.
For whom did you work then?
David S. Castle.
And that was, what was, was that a contractor or an architect?
Architect, engineer.
Did he specialize in any particular kind of building?
We did principally educational and institutional commercial work.
Very little residential work of that type.
Has that been sort of what you've done pretty much all the time?
Yes.
Institutional rather than residential.
Have you done any residential work?
Yes, some.
So you were with Castle?
Yes.
Who were some of the other people for whom you worked?
Well, when I left there I went to San Antonio.
I was with Adams and Adams down there for about a year.
And then I went to Lubbock with Peter Strange and Bradshaw.
And we were there until the Depression got us.
Which was what, about 1929 or 30?
Well, we had work that lasted through until 32.
And we went over to the oil boom in Longview in 32.
And so was there a lot of building going on because of the oil boom?
Yes.
And so did the whole office move from Lubbock to?
By degrees.
We didn't intend to, but we did before we left.
And so you stayed with Peters then?
Yes.
Right on through until when?
Oh, until World War II.
He was an Aggie.
He was a senior when I was a freshman.
This was Peters?
M.L.
Peters.
Uh-huh.
And at the beginning of World War II then, what, you left Peters and went to somebody else?
Well we went into this defense work that I told you about of building the Longhorn Ordinance over on Caddo and then we went together up to Canada.
And then where'd you go to after that?
From Canada I came back and I was out in the Mahoga Desert for almost a year again on
we were constructing a naval armaments test station at Inyo Kern.
At where?
Inyo Kern.
And then after that you went where?
After that I came back and went in business here.
In Amarillo?
Yes.
How did you happen to choose Amarillo?
Well when I was in Lubbock I had become quite familiar with Amarillo and had friends up here.
Okay, so you were, what was the name of the company that you were in?
Guy A. Carlander.
Guy A. Carlander.
Yes.
And how long were you with that?
I was with him again about seven years and then I left and
three of us organized our own office here.
And that was what?
Howard Ensign was the name that went under Ensign and Fowler and Wright.
And you have since retired, I take it?
Yes, I was with Ensign until I retired the first of January in 69.
So you've continued to live in Amarillo since and have continued your artwork.
Yes.
Are you active in any other endeavors?
Not particularly.
Of course, I'm a member of the American Institute of Architects and the Texas Society of Architects and the Panhandle chapter.
And except the local.
Going back to your career for a little bit, I believe before we started the machine earlier, you indicated that you did a good bit of watercolor of the sketches of buildings.
Right.
That, I take it, was your specialty with the various companies?
No, no.
There's not enough of that required.
I did general work, a great deal of designing.
Well then, would the company then have somebody else who would take over those plans and see that the contractor followed them in construction?
Yes.
Did you ever do much of that?
A little bit, not much.
Could you indicate a few of the other jobs on which you worked?
Any outstanding buildings that you can think of?
Two of my favorites are the high school down at Lubbock High School, they call it now.
And that was built when?
And I'm quite proud of that job.
It's still being used and added to.
And it's one of their big high schools down there.
And I enjoyed very much the first Presbyterian church in Kilgore, Texas.
Fortunately, they had good funds over there, and they allowed us to do a real nice Gothic church.
I gather they have a good bit of oil money over there, do they not?
Oh yes.
And when was that one, when did you design that one?
In about 39 and 40.
So it was in the, just before the war then, wasn't it?
Yes.
Any other ones which kind of stick out in your memory?
Well, we've done quite a bit of church work.
I also like the First Presbyterian Church.
Mr. Peters was a presbyterian, as you may have gathered, in Longyear.
It's a nice church.
Was that another one that was done during the oil boom?
Late part of it, yes, latter part of it.
And did you begin with the idea and then put the idea on paper, or is that basically what you did?
Well, you don't have a whole idea at once.
You develop the thing by stages and whatnot.
When you sit down, say, to design a church, do you draw the profile first and then the floor plan, or do you do the floor plan first and then the...
Well, you spend a lot of time studying their problem and their organization of the different Sunday school and different departments.
And then you begin to put together units to fit those various things.
And then you tie them all together, basically with a floor plan first, but keeping in mind what it's going to look like in perspective.
I suppose you could do a very utilitarian building that wouldn't look very nice, and you could also do a building that looks very nice, but it's not very utilitarian.
Quite right.
So I suppose the ideal is to get a combination of the two.
Yes.
The present accent is more on a good plan that's workable and serviceable and let the exterior fall where it will.
Back when I started, it was the other way.
Exterior was an important thing, and maybe you'd cramp the plan or what a little bit to fit into the type of exterior you wanted.
I've had very little personal contact with architects, but I have heard, well, I lived in New England for a number of years, and I've heard a number of people there who complained

A neighboring community to us built a large new high school and for some reason or other the architect had installed a number of things which were kind of superfluous really for the school and it really increased the taxes.
I think he put in a large mural on the exterior which made the school look nice but he didn't make it a better school.
Were some of the, were the, you mentioned that when you first started the emphasis was on an outward appearance.
Did, would this include such things as, as murals and... Oh no, most of the work then was classic.
And classic is severely balanced.
Maybe a continuous deal and terminations and all of those motifs and uh...
That was the principal thing in the design, and then if you had to cramp the exterior, the interior a little bit to fit into that as a floor plan, you did.
Now with buildings not away from the classic theme, it's easier to do units that are more varied and more flexible.

But you would think that today's architect works with, say, an organization needs a specific floor space and he has to stick with that and the space requirements take precedence over the outward appearance.
Yes.
Does that bother you at all?
Not at all.
Not at all.
I think it's...
natural result.

What would you say had been some of the, in addition to this, say the shift from outward appearance to emphasis on space considerations, what else have been some fairly significant developments in architecture and construction over the past number of years
Well, of course, the primary thing is our use of steel, which opened up possibilities that were limited before.
There's a lot of difference in how much you can span with steel as compared to putting a stone lintel over two posts.
What about glass?
Frankly, I think glass has been overdone.
You didn't ask for my opinion, but I couldn't help but throw it in.
We have made all glass exteriors, and then we go in and have to curtain the light to subdue it, and we have to add extra air conditioning because of the heat infiltration and all of those things.
I think there's a happy medium there.
In other words, you think there ought to be a few more bricks and a little less glass?
A little more masonry, let's say, to break people getting mad at us.
Well, I gather the ever-increasing amounts of steel would be one of those things which would permit a greater use of glass.
Yes.
A little more time.
Anything, any other comments you would care to make on...
developments, say recent developments in architecture?
No, I don't feel like I'm qualified to comment.
My day has passed.
Since you have retired, have you dabbled in any kind of architecture other than the painting you do?
No, I practiced architecture until I was 70 and then I thought it was time for me to quit and let the younger fellas take over.
So have you done any kind of consulting?
Have you looked over a set of plans to see that they were ?
No, no one has asked that.
